{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512889"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11971"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11971"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.79,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109452"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91817"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"3346"},{"type":"tags","id":"3448"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109452"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner complaining of epigastric pain, particularly between meals and at night. She has no other gastrointestinal symptoms. She is overweight (BMI 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E), but is otherwise in good health. She does not take any regular medications and has not been unwell recently. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is started on a proton pump inhibitor and referred for an upper GI endoscopy within two weeks. The results of the endoscopy determine that she has a small gastric ulcer with histology confirming inflammatory changes and the presence of \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Ebacteria. She is placed on triple therapy (esomeprazole, amoxicillin and clarithromycin) for 14 days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following follow-up is most appropriate to confirm the eradication of H.pylori?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Upper GI endoscopy four weeks post antibiotic therapy completion","Clinical re-evaluation four weeks post antibiotic therapy completion","Urea breath test four weeks post antibiotic therapy and two weeks post PPI therapy","Serological testing for antibodies","Stool antigen test two weeks post antibiotic therapy and two weeks post PPI therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with confirmed \u003Cem\u003EH.pylori \u003C/em\u003Einfection it is beneficial for the patient and better utilises medical resources to ensure that effective eradication has occurred. Eradication confirmation leads to fewer patients being repeatedly treated with inefficient drug combinations and reduce the burden on healthcare funding by requiring further treatment regimens. There are multiple options available to clinicians to determine if the infection has been eradicated. This includes repeat endoscopy, urea breath testing, stool antigen testing and serological testing for antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen patients are prescribed triple therapy consisting of 2x antibiotics and a PPI (esomeprazole, amoxicillin and clarithromycin), they require a\u003Cstrong\u003E four week washout period from the antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E to accurately determine if the infection with H. pylori has truly been eradicated. Similarly, they will also require a \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo week washout period from the PPI \u003C/strong\u003Etherapy as this medication may also produce false negative results by suppression of bacterial activity that are still present in the stomach. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient will also require an \u003Cstrong\u003Eupper GI endoscopy four weeks after antibiotic therapy completion\u003C/strong\u003E, however the purpose of this is not to check for the eradication of \u003Cem\u003EH.pylori \u003C/em\u003Ebut to ensure that the ulcer is healing and to rule out the presence of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the other incorrect answers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool antigen test two weeks post antibiotic therapy and two weeks post PPI therapy, \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect as the timeframes are incorrect for effective washout of medications to have occurred. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical re-evaluation four weeks post antibiotic therapy completion \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect as more accurate means of confirming eradication are required as above for better healthcare outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerological testing for antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated as a reliable test for confirmation of\u003Cem\u003E H. Pylori \u003C/em\u003Eeradication. This is due to patients often still having circulating antibodies post eradication, providing an incorrect representation of eradication status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Confirmation of the eradication of H.pylori infection is good medical practice."],"references":["Chey WD, Leontiadis GI, Howden CW, Moss SF. ACG Clinical Guideline: Treatment of Helicobacter pylori Infection. Am J Gastroenterol. 2017 Feb;112(2):212-239. doi: 10.1038/ajg.2016.563. Epub 2017 Jan 10. Erratum in: Am J Gastroenterol. 2018 Jul;113(7):1102. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28071659/","Stenstr\u00f6m B, Mendis A, Marshall B. Helicobacter pylori: the latest in diagnosis and treatment. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2008 Aug 1;37(8):608. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18704207/","Cutler AF, Toskes P. Comparison of [13C]urea blood test to [13C]urea breath test for the diagnosis of Helicobacter pylori. Am J Gastroenterol. 1999 Apr;94(4):959-61. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10201464/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91817"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11971"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91817"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T15:47:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T15:49:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4563"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109452"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}